Node.Notes: With two Hebrew manuscripts and a Qumran manuscript, some prefer singular "his chosen one," which would be in apposition to "Jacob." Text is plural and is in apposition to "sons of Jacob."
Tree assumes something like "[remember the covenant] which he cut with Abrahaam and his oath to Isaac"
Tree assumes "[when they were] as few [in number]."
Tree assumes "[when they were] strangers in her."
Some think "his soul" sometimes can refer to the neck (e.g., ps69:1) and that the "iron" is an iron collar. Tree assumes "his person entered fetters."
Tree assumes either "[the king put him in charge]..." from previous verse or simply "[the king did this]..."
Literally, "to bind/imprison." Many see "bind" in sense of exercising authority over. Many others follow LXX and change word slightly to yield "to instruct/discipline."

Uncertain what "words/matters of his signs" means. Some see "words" as referring to Moses' and Aaron's predictions of the plagues or God's commands to them. Many simply treat as "matters" and omit it in translation (giving just 'his signs").
Uncertain. Some omit negative. Others explain shift in perspective as referring to either Moses and Aaron or the Israelites.
Tree assumes verb "came" from previous clause carries over.
Text has "he asked," which could refer to Moses. Others think it is impersonal and so could be "one asked" in the sense of they asked. Others follow ancient versions and give plural "they asked."
Uncertain. Tree assumes "the word of his holiness with Abraham his servant."
